metadata.name: Syzers #398
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

¬∑¬∑¬∑¬∑ On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ¬∑¬∑¬∑¬∑

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template. 
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

metadata.name: Skravert #131
metadata.description:
‚ÄòSkravert‚Äô - Norwegian, verb, past tense. ‚ÄòThe act of filling an area with lines; to shade an area‚Äô.

Skravert is a series of 320 sketches, each capturing the texture and feel of a material residing somewhere between cardboard and woolen rugs. The project is centred around rectangle subdivision and a line drawing algorithm, giving each piece its own unique expression when combined with a selection of 28 different color  palettes.  

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2021

metadata.name: Shift #195
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm honing the power of vertical displacement.

How simple may a generative algorithm be while simultaneously staying diverse enough for each art piece to be truly unique? Shift is the result of an exploration into this space, basing its existence on two principles ‚Äî dissection and vertical shifting. Each variable in this art engine has been meticulously weighted, giving rise to high diversity and the possibility of epic combinations. 

Shift is a series of 888 unique pieces.

############

Display resolution is 1000x1400. Press ‚Äôs‚Äô (in live mode) to generate a 6000x8400 hi-res image. This may take a while to generate depending on your hardware.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: aether:Astral Loom #49
metadata.description:
Weaving on the astral plane. Lines of transmission. 
Some journeys are straightforward, others yield a multitude of pathways.
Disconnect to interpret.

(As an experiment) the rarity values assigned to this artwork are completely arbitrary, and are in no way connected to the visual output of the minted piece. One might wonder, why have rarity values at all? That's what I ask myself any time I see a value based on rarity attributes instead of viewer aesthetic. 

That being said, I suppose it's up to each person to decide for themselves the value of art...

This artwork was created using p5js.

metadata.name: Mur #15
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: For Better Dreams #150
metadata.description:
A radiant talisman. Watchful third eye. Use as directed.

Once minted your patterns maintain their design while stretching to accommodate changes in canvas size.

There are no rarity attributes assigned to this artwork, its value is intended to be determined by viewer aesthetic alone. That aside, there are 6 possible color palettes and 7 possible background colors. 

This artwork was created using p5js and utilizes the p5.pattern library created by Taichi Sayama.
